Barack Obama to be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will receive them, inter alia, for the exceptional effort to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The chief of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have much to do.
First, visit to the Nobel Institute, where for the first time you will meet the five members of the committee that, in October, elected you between 172 people and 33 organizations.
Then the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate in a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, although the third one to receive it in his office.
The White House has already announced that when it receives the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President did not want to avoid that issue, knowing that he was receiving the prize as president of a country currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the dispatch of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he did not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to donate them to charitable purposes, but it has not yet decided to which organization in particular.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
