A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in 'breasted' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds able to moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some accessible medicines already.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, patients' lives can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all the medicines used today, so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved' compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus albumin.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the protease of HIV, there is no fractionation of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this set of substances against HIV proteases was performed as a sample, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as on the clinically used medicines, however they do not lose their effect on the resistant variants, in which the drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the single effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications makes, that the metalocarborans are interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína, the head of the laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of Organic and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
