In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have performed abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to an unnaturally high male-female ratio.
In recent years, population officials have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 they attenuated many of their hardline slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Demographic Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government officials have recently been debating even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost at night in the morning, posters ordering families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide brochures under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very little overwhelming.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai maintain that they have seen a moderate increase in requests for couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban districts do not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only around 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Municipality's family planning committee in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want children anymore.
They want to give their first child the best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally qualified to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly see the one-child policy as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the first child of the couple.
Yeah, they're robbing us of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources manager, said he wants an only child because she too was: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and we really don't want to care for others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years old, owner of a translation agency, explained it more forcefully.
For parents with two middle-class careers, who reduce the birth rate, he said, it's about having enough success to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up watching their parents' struggle during the first days of China's experiment with capitalism and do not want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from parents, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are questions of space, "they have to remodel their apartment," and the strategic "must have a curriculum prepared for the best day care centers when the child is 9 months old."
