We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give to the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the overall temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page paper, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent during the same period.
Together, countries would cut emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the talks last week.
The US Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected claims requesting mandatory greenhouse gas emission reductions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs He Yafei, said that the top climate negotiator in the United States lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to hold the major emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, Ulate said, who also works as a regional climate change adviser for International Conservation in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the talks will produce a political agreement at most.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States prepared a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early in the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," in part because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks assumed a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government can close a deal.
High-level officials, such as Indian Minister of Environment Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran into the corridors of the Bella Center, closed-door meetings and press conferences, in order to be able to delimit the claims that will be arbitrated during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention center every day, the activists who play the guitar present night shows mocking the countries they say are selling, and preliminary proposals are passed hand-in-hand instead of via email), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all the key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of International Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
