Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before, it was a question of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave place to the strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the preference factors of the customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a forward-looking vision; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authority.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would be to put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
-Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic vision of human behavior.
As they come from major engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the ancient conductist theory that the American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a position of mechanical management, unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is possible only if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only the studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of the employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, company managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
