Turkish justice dissolves prokurdo party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favour of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately provoked demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the government's task, which has just given the Kurdish community a hand in trying to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that undermined the independence of the State and its indivisible unity," the President of the Court, Hasim Kiliç, told the press after four days of discussions.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a seven-vote majority was needed to obtain the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are separated from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's property by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament before they were parliamentarians without a party label.
The decision follows a procedure launched by Supreme Court Prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007, accusing the DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Many observers believe that DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims that it does not have "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict of the Court intervenes at the moment when the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus put an end to the conflict.
DTP leaders stated that a dissolution could lead to an upsurge in tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police over the past few weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the great city of the Southeast mostly inhabited by Kurds.
The Order Forces threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov bombs or rocks with slings.
In Istanbul, about 100 people were also concentrated.
After the verdict, Türk stated that the decision of the justice system was "to deepen discouragement."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdah, NDLR) by dissolving a party, it told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
At first we oppose the closure of parties.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic opening launched by the government, political analyst Ahmet Insel commented.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
This Thursday, the PKK was attacked in which seven soldiers died three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
