The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa found looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa found was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the sages were divided into their three most important genealogical lines: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (sauri with bird pelvis), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus belong.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also owned by the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa he also found the bones of the spine were evidently partially full of air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the posterior giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known were living in South America, researchers deduce that the sages first appeared there.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines were separated at the beginning and extended from South America throughout all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single earth mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa found the remains of two other teropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a unique related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three waves of migration to North America took place, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of Science.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a brotherly group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs continue to be preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other sages.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship was extinguished at the limit of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
The successful stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, an impact of meteorite brake the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
