Oniric worlds
In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and in the drug addicts, the limits between imagination and reality fade.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can give ourselves unhindered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during the vigil, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is considered most of the time in the modern Western world to be crazy or drug addict, or at least to be a maniac.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
The fault is our imagination: the same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to be blurred.
Onirically modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the prophet of the New Age Carlos Castañeda, the states of Chamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or deliriums arise when the balance of the neuronal substances of communication in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been untied and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis very often complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the misconceptions, crazy formations, and mirrorisms of it".
It's the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and scandalously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it's floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red mussels like blood, deformed, snorting their teeth.
They're chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over the body.
Strict and malignant voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can't stand them anymore, the voices that insult him and offend him.
Henning T. starts two wires from the stereo, ties them to form a hanging knot, and fixes them to a hook on the ceiling.
He goes up into a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
"Go to the clinic and make them heal you!" the voices shout in a choir that blows his eardrums.
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychosis, the last one two years ago, the first one almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was the LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, and he is manic-depressive, he takes drugs, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he has been married.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; psychiatric clinics treat it as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the times those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and they fall into a state of overexcitedness that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, disorders in the relationship, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the gates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatric clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
That is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
The paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For the researchers still an unknown why our brain makes cabrioles.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality on an interim basis.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother's viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it is still an unknown how this alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a previous disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain's transmitting system.
When the brain heats up
The logic of all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive medicines to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says Professor Erich Kasten, of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The Unreal World in Our Head), published last year.
The hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with mental disorders such as personality limit disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and head trauma .
in a surprising way and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memories that are usually repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly cohibited; when our brain gets warm, but also when there is a lack of stimuli.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, the evil of love or other states of emergency brain.
