Seventy-five per cent of working mothers have had labour problems because of their motherhood.
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career path of women in Spain', developed by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences at the beginning of the couple's cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they perform.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unsteady job, start living together as a couple before, advance the first motherhood, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay living together and motherhood, and have less offspring.
"Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting living together, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their vital trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a great deal of influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of the pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women by marrying and having the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and have the first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education had been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"There is also another division between women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado explains.
