Aid for emergency braking is already compulsory
As with ABS brake antilock and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all passenger cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection but, by its way of work, can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency brake assistant does what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the footset given by the driver.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had failed to step on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study itself, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided a year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
